+You are an expert Python and bash developer building an evolutionary parameter tuning system for automated trading (V2 Lego Block architecture).
+
+Task title: Implement The V2 Mutation Engine
+
+Objective: Replace obsolete mutate.py with a new single-parameter, bounds-aware mutation system that safely perturbs config_v2.json parameters.
+
+Files to create:
+
+File 1 - path: scripts/mutate_v2.py
+Language: Python 3
+Purpose: Load config_v2.json, randomly select and mutate exactly one parameter according to strict rules, enforce constraints, log change, save file, print feedback.
+
+Input file: config_v2.json (valid JSON, utf-8)
+Output file: config_v2.json (overwrite, indent=4)
+Log file: user_data/logs/evolution.log (append mode, create parent dirs if missing)
+
+Mutation target selection: uniform random choice among the following 10 parameters
+Parameter mutation rules (name | type | step options | bounds | extra constraints):
+
+rsi_period     integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     min:7   max:30    no extra
+buy_rsi        integer   step: -5,5           min:10  max:90    no extra
+sell_rsi       integer   step: -5,5           min:10  max:90    no extra
+macd_fast      integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     must remain < macd_slow after mutation
+macd_slow      integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     must remain > macd_fast after mutation
+macd_signal    integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     min:5   max:20
+bb_length      integer   steps: -2,2          min:5   max:50
+bb_std         float     step: -0.1,0.1       min:1.0 max:4.0   round to 1 decimal place
+ema_fast       integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     must remain < ema_slow after mutation
+ema_slow       integer   steps: -2,-1,1,2     must remain > ema_fast after mutation
+
+Mutation logic requirements:
+- select exactly one parameter name randomly
+- select one valid step from its allowed steps randomly
+- compute candidate new value = current + step
+- if integer → int(candidate)
+- if float (only bb_std) → round(candidate, 1)
+- check hard min/max bounds → if violation, re-roll step until valid (max 20 attempts, else skip mutation)
+- for macd_fast/slow and ema_fast/slow: after applying step, verify fast < slow → if violation, either reverse step direction or skip this mutation attempt
+- simplest safe strategy: mutate only one of the pair at a time and reject move if constraint broken
+- print exactly: Mutated {param_name}: {old_value} → {new_value}
+- log line format: YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS | Mutated {param_name}: {old_value} → {new_value} | generation={current_generation}   (generation number passed as optional cli arg or omitted)
+- use json.dump with indent=4, ensure_ascii=False when saving
+- import: random, json, os, datetime, pathlib
+
+File 2 - path: scripts/evolve_v2.sh
+Language: bash
+Shebang: #!/usr/bin/env bash
+Options: set -euo pipefail
+Environment: export PYTHONPATH=.
+
+Behavior:
+- create directory user_data/logs if not exists (mkdir -p)
+- loop 10 generations (i from 1 to 10 inclusive)
+- inside loop:
+  - echo "Starting generation $i"
+  - python3 scripts/mutate_v2.py
+  - ./scripts/validate_and_save.sh
+  - python3 scripts/gauntlet.py V2Assembler
+  - git add .
+  - git commit -m "Evolve: Generation $i - Score PLACEHOLDER" || true
+  - git push origin main
+  - sleep 2
+
+Additional global requirements:
+- all paths are relative to project root
+- scripts must create missing directories automatically when needed
+- log file must be appended after each successful mutation (mutate_v2.py responsibility)
+- no decorative output beyond the required print and log lines
+
+Deliverables expected: complete source code for both files with comments explaining constraint handling and re-roll logic

# 2026-03-05 17:36:11.829782
+You are an expert in vectorized pandas-based technical analysis.
+
+Task: Create the initial version of the Genetic Programming primitive library for trading signals.
+
+Target file: user_data/strategies/gp_blocks.py
+
+Requirements:
+
+Imports (exactly these, at the top):
+import pandas as pd
+import numpy as np
+import pandas_ta as ta
+from typing import Union, Tuple
+
+Implement these functions (all fully vectorized, no loops, no .apply):
+
+Indicator functions – all return pd.Series unless otherwise stated:
+
+def get_rsi(df: pd.DataFrame, window: int = 14) -> pd.Series:
+    Use ta.rsi(close=df['close'], length=window)
+
+def get_ema(df: pd.DataFrame, window: int) -> pd.Series:
+    Use ta.ema(close=df['close'], length=window)
+
+def get_sma(df: pd.DataFrame, window: int) -> pd.Series:
+    Use ta.sma(close=df['close'], length=window)
+
+def get_bollinger(df: pd.DataFrame, window: int = 20, std: float = 2.0) -> Tuple[pd.Series, pd.Series, pd.Series]:
+    bb = ta.bbands(close=df['close'], length=window, std=std)
+    Return bb[f'BBU_{window}_{std}'], bb[f'BBM_{window}_{std}'], bb[f'BBL_{window}_{std}']
+
+Comparator functions – all return pd.Series[bool]:
+
+def greater_than(s1: pd.Series, s2: Union[pd.Series, float, int]) -> pd.Series:
+    Return s1 > s2
+
+def less_than(s1: pd.Series, s2: Union[pd.Series, float, int]) -> pd.Series:
+    Return s1 < s2
+
+def cross_up(s1: pd.Series, threshold: Union[pd.Series, float, int]) -> pd.Series:
+    Return (s1.shift(1) <= threshold) & (s1 > threshold)
+
+def cross_down(s1: pd.Series, threshold: Union[pd.Series, float, int]) -> pd.Series:
+    Return (s1.shift(1) >= threshold) & (s1 < threshold)
+
+Add concise docstring to every function (one or two lines explaining purpose and return type).
+
+Assumptions:
+- Input df contains at minimum columns: close (required), high, low, volume (expected for future extensions)
+- Data is time-sorted ascending
+
+At the very bottom of the file add exactly:
+if __name__ == "__main__":
+    print("GP Blocks library loaded.")

